image.altText: Two men smiling

props.synopsis: New South Wales Police have charged a constable with two counts of murder after the disappearance of a Sydney couple. Here's what we know.

title.children: What is known about the alleged double murder of Luke Davies and Jesse Baird

image.altText: A composite image of Beau Lamarre, Luke Davies and Jesse Baird

props.synopsis: Beau Lamarre-Condon has appeared before Waverley Local Court after he was charged with the murder of Luke Davies and Jesse Baird who disappeared under suspicious circumstances this week.

title.children: Police officer faces court for the first time charged with murder after Sydney couple disappears

image.altText: Beau Lamarre stands smiling beside celebrity Taylor Swift

props.synopsis: A man is in police custody, connected to the disappearance of a Sydney couple, but who is Beau Lamarre, and what can his celebrity-obsessed past tell the police?

title.children: Celebrity-chaser turned cop: Who is the man connected to the disappearance of a Sydney couple?

image.altText: Fans at accor stadium

props.synopsis: Chaos has hit tonight's Taylor Swift concert in Sydney with thousands of fans being evacuated after lightning strikes near the venue.

title.children: Swifties evacuated, warned to seek shelter as storms, lightning delay US megastar's first Sydney show

image.altText: rocky

props.synopsis: Rocky Harvey says he dumped the head outside the office in Jindabyne as an act of protest against culled brumby carcasses being left to pollute Kosciuszko National Park.

title.children: Protestor who dumped horse head outside National Parks office avoids conviction record

image.altText: close up of a young woman's face

props.synopsis: Natasha Lechner died of heart failure just minutes after taking part in a kambo ritual, with the NSW coroner finding the giant tree frog poison can cause death in healthy people as well as those with pre-existing conditions.

title.children: Kambo guidelines do not reveal 'true risk' of using frog poison, NSW coroner finds

image.altText: An artfully put together red, black and white graphic depicts a group of students walking down a university hallway.

props.synopsis: State, territory and federal education ministers have agreed to a national action plan to tackle sexual assault on university campuses, with student activists labelling the suite of reforms groundbreaking and transformative.

title.children: National plan to reduce sexual violence at universities to be implemented

image.altText: A smiling blond woman

props.synopsis: Investigators say they believe "more parties" are involved in the Ballarat mother's disappearance and "everyone" in her life is a person of interest as the search focuses on bushland south of Ballarat.

title.children: Samantha Murphy most likely dead, police say, as phone clue leads to new search

image.altText: A split image showing a woman and a little boy in a small helicopter and pop star Taylor Swift performing.

props.synopsis: Ex-Tropical Cyclone Lincoln has proven no match for Taylor Swift, whose fans from the outback have pulled out all the stops to get to Sydney despite heavy flooding.

title.children: The cruel summer that nearly stopped Maddie and Madi from making it to Taylor Swift

image.altText: A wide shot of a tree-lined path running along a beach.

props.synopsis: Holes that may have been used to deliver pesticides were discovered this week after a resident reported seeing a man acting suspiciously in the area.

title.children: Nine Port Jackson fig trees vandalised at Sydney beach

image.altText: Network Ten CEO Beverley McGarvey

props.synopsis: Speaking about the difficulty of finding Australian networks on smart TVs, Network Ten's chief content officer said despite being tech savvy, it took her almost an hour with an engineer's help to get her own company's app downloaded on her television.

title.children: Network Ten exec needed almost an hour and help to download 10Play app

image.altText: A wristband that reads "Taylor Swift", with a small compartment containing LEDs.

props.synopsis: A mother who lost her child under tragic circumstances has raised concerns about the LED wristbands given to fans attending Taylor Swift's concerts.

title.children: Warning issued to hundreds of thousands of Swifties amid concerns about Eras Tour wristbands

image.altText: A man walks out of the doors of the ACT law courts.

props.synopsis: Bruce Shillingsworth Jr receives an 18-month suspended sentence for his role in a fire that caused millions of dollars in damage to the entrance of Old Parliament House in Canberra.

title.children: 'Charismatic leader' avoids jail over Canberra protests that saw doors to Old Parliament House set alight

image.altText: two young school boys walk to school wearing backpacks as one puts his arm around the others shoulder

props.synopsis: A new analysis of school funding reveals five elite private schools in New South Wales and Victoria spent more on new facilities in 2021 than half of the nation's public schools.

title.children: Private schools building 'office towers and Scottish castles' while public schools left with demountable classrooms, union says

image.altText: A close-up of a smartphone displaying an Nvidia logo, sandwiched between two computer parts.

props.synopsis: Chipmaker Nvidia has just recorded the biggest one-day gain by any company in Wall Street history. But could the AI boom be just another dot-com-style bubble?

title.children: 'They are literally printing money on silicon': AI sends Nvidia's market value soaring higher than Australia's GDP

image.altText: A close up of Taylor Swift on stage, wearing a bejewelled leotard.

props.synopsis: Concert organisers say the pop star will play "rain or shine", saying the only exception would be in the case of severe weather which could risk the safety of Swift and fans.

title.children: There's a high chance of heavy rain and storms in Sydney tonight but Taylor Swift's concert will go on unless it's 'severe'

image.altText: Court sketch of Snowtown accomplice Mark Ray Haydon sitting in the dock.

props.synopsis: The South Australian government will argue in court that bodies-in-the-barrels accomplice Mark Ray Haydon poses an "appreciable risk to the safety of the community if not supervised".

title.children: Snowtown accomplice Mark Haydon poses 'appreciable risk', court document alleges

image.altText: A fire burning a tree next to a house with orange skies.

props.synopsis: Emergency crews are continuing to battle a large bushfire west of Ballarat in Victoria, with authorities urging nearby residents to leave immediately.

title.children: Conditions expected to ease as fire crews battle to contain blaze in Victoria's west

liveBlogKeyEvents.title: UPDATE: Emergency warnings replaced but it is not safe to return
UPDATE: Emergency warnings as of 4:05pm AEDT

image.altText: A close up of a young girl wearing a pink jumper standing in front of rubble.

props.synopsis: In Gaza, Maazize is feeding her children ground up animal food and tea made from sticks and leaves, just so they have something in their starving stomachs.

title.children: As famine grips Gaza, this family experiences stomach cramps after a meal of animal feed and sticks

image.altText: An aerial view of a Sydney-to-Melbourne train that derailed near Wallan on February 20, 2020.

props.synopsis: Train companies plead guilty to breaching rail safety laws in wake of fatal train crash north of Melbourne.

title.children: Train companies admit safety failures in deadly derailment near Melbourne

image.altText: Justin Tatum holds a basketball inside a basketball stadium wearing a black polo shirt.

props.synopsis: Justin Tatum, who has one of the most famous surnames in the NBA, has been signed to permanently lead the Illawarra Hawks NBL team.

title.children: NBA superstar's dad appointed as NBL team's head coach after inspiring dramatic season revival

image.altText: A mother and daughter pose for a photo

props.synopsis: Some 3,790 Ukrainians who fled the Russian invasion are in Australia on three-year temporary humanitarian visas, but they are due to expire.

title.children: Ukrainians in Australia have limited time left on their visas but there's no end in sight to the war in their home country

image.altText: Taylor Swift close up on stage, smiling

props.synopsis: On the Telstra network alone, concertgoers at Taylor Swift's Melbourne shows used around 34.85 TB of data, or 12 TB each night  — that's the equivalent of 15,500 hours of video, lasting 1.7 years if it was played continuously.

title.children: Are telco networks becoming more fragile? Taylor Swift's Melbourne shows could be a preview of what's to come

image.altText: A crack in the Ranchi pitch before the fourth Test between India and England.

props.synopsis: The pitch in Ranchi for the fourth Test between India and England was described as looking like "a dried-up riverbed" by one former player with the series on the line.

title.children: 'It looks a little dry': England capitulates on 'dried-up riverbed' of a pitch in Ranchi

image.altText: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese speaks to the press club in a stern, close-up shot

props.synopsis: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese says Coles and Woolworths "clearly have excessive market power", but he rejects any suggestion of introducing divestiture powers.

title.children: Prime Minister says something 'going wrong' on supermarket pricing, but won't break up Coles and Woolworths duopoly

image.altText: A large wild boar standing on some grass.

props.synopsis: A letter from members of a rural crime unit within the NSW police force has called for pig dogs to be made illegal because of animal welfare concerns and the considerable resources consumed in the effort to prevent trespassing.

title.children: Police call for pig dog ban, but hunters say rural officers 'not getting the job done'

image.altText: A general view of Victoria Park, where bonded asbestos was found in mulch

props.synopsis: Widespread asbestos contamination of mulch has left residents of Sydney and Canberra worried, but experts say it does not pose a "significant risk".  We unpack how asbestos causes health issues and what kinds of exposure are harmful.

title.children: What's the risk of inhaling asbestos from contaminated mulch if you stroll through a park?

image.altText: A spaceship looking back to Australia

props.synopsis: Scientists from the CSIRO and Parkes Observatory have helped the United States land a craft on the Moon, part of a plan to send humans there for the first time since the Apollo missions.

title.children: US back on the Moon for the first time in 52 years, and Australian scientists helped it get there

image.altText: Julian Assange looks to the camera as he is photographed from behind glass with graffiti etched into it. His grey hair is back.

props.synopsis: The Australian's legal avenues to avoid extradition from Britain to the US are running out, but something in London gave his supporters hope this week, and it wasn't inside the courtroom.

title.children: Julian Assange has been back in court, but it was something outside that got people talking

image.altText: Madison de Rozario smiles

props.synopsis: This year's London Marathon will award equal prize money to able-bodied and wheelchair athletes, the first major marathon in the world to do so in a "landmark" move for equality in sport.

title.children: London Marathon's 'beautiful' move for full equality praised by athletes

image.altText: Yellow cardboard hand painted protest signs on the Appin traffic sign

props.synopsis: Michelle Maroun says homemade signs protesting a proposed 13,000-home development in a village of about 2,600 people were pulled down by crews under the instructions of its developer the morning after residents put them up.

title.children: Housing development opponent 'furious' after protest signs pulled down allegedly under instructions of developer
